tags.note: This is probably the correct location, right where GNIS had it. The original downtown area would have been just south in the quarry.

tags.name: Chelsea
tags.note: Incorporated in 1889, Surveyed and platted in 1902. Oil was discovered in 1890, this was the first oil well in Oklahoma. Chelsea has 3 buildings on the National Historic Register.

tags.description: Named for the town's first resident & post master, Alfred Foyil. The post office opened in 1890.
tags.name: Foyil
North Miami
tags.note: North Miami received it's Postal Designation in 1915 and was located roughly on the boarder of the Quapaw lands to the north and Peoria lands to the south.

tags.description: The Atlantic and Pacific Railway expanded in the area in 1876. Afton's Post office was established in 1886.
tags.name: Afton

tags.description: Incorporated in 1902, named for Narcissa Owen Walker, daughter of Postmaster of the Indian Territory (which became Oklahoma). The town had a historic gas station, but that has since been demolished.
tags.name: Narcissa

tags.description: Post Office opened in Quapaw in 1897 inside the grocery store. A "New" Quapaw was platted east of the original and incorporated in 1917. By 1920 there were 1,394 residents. By 1933 Route 66 was paved through the county.
tags.name: Quapaw

tags.description: Post Office opened in 1898 and closed in 1957.
tags.name: White Oak

tags.description: Founded in 1891, Miami is the capitol of the Miami, Modoc, and Ottawa Tribes of Oklahoma, and the Peoria and Shawnee Tribes.
tags.name: Miami

tags.description: Named for Dennis W Bushyhead, the principal chief of the Cherokee (1878-1887), Post office opened in April, 1898 and closed in November, 1955.
tags.name: Bushyhead
